        "orario": "07:00",
        "timestamp": 1772690409,
        "contenuto_esteso": "‘War can be so close’: China newlyweds separated by US strikes on Iran during Doha honeymoon | South China Morning Post Advertisement Trending in China People & Culture Trending in China ‘War can be so close’: China newlyweds separated by US strikes on Iran during Doha honeymoon Stranded husband decides to save money, hassle by staying behind in conflict-hit city as wife flies out before region’s airports shut down 2 -MIN READ 2 -MIN Fran Lu in Beijing Published: 2:00pm, 5 Mar 2026 A honeymooning Chinese couple have been separated by the US-Israel strikes on Iran, which caused airspace closures across the Middle East and reportedly affected more than a million passengers. The newlywed couple, from eastern China’s Zhejiang province, travelled to the Middle East on February 19 to enjoy its beautiful sunset scenery. Doha was the last stop of their trip. A missile lights up the night sky in Doha as conflict rages in the Middle East. Photo: QQ.com They exchanged their airline credits for business class tickets from Doha to Sydney as the husband, surnamed Yu, works in Melbourne. However, because of the airline’s policy, they did not get tickets for the same day. Advertisement The wife, surnamed Zheng, got a ticket for the 9am flight on February 28. Yu got a ticket for the same flight the next day. The US and Israel launched strikes against Iran on February 28. Advertisement Three major Middle East hubs, Dubai, Abu Dhabi and Doha, shut down their airports. Advertisement Select Voice Select Speed 0.8x 0.9x 1.0x 1.1x 1.2x 1.5x 1.75x 00:00 00:00 1.00 x"
